In the midst of searching for a modification that would allow the rifle to function without excessive barrel recoil or venting, he accidentally learned of a 1915 bolt patent to US Navy officer John Blish. Russian operated on the principle of adhesion of inclined metal surfaces under pressure [27]. Having received financial support from Thomas Ryan (English) Russian, Thompson founded the Auto-Ordnance Company (English) Russian to manufacture and market his new rifle. It was originally produced in Cleveland ( Ohio State)[28]. The development team included engineers Theodore Eickhoff, Oscar Payne and George Goll, who developed the semi-free shutter system[21][12].